WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.510 --> 00:00:17.749
Julie Stout: Okay, I think we are set. So, hello again. My name is Julie Sao, and I'm here with John Hasse. I am… it is currently March 18th, 2026, and I'm currently in Bloomington, Indiana. And John, will you remind me where you're at?

2
00:00:18.640 --> 00:00:19.650
John Hasse: I am in.

3
00:00:19.830 --> 00:00:23.910
John Hasse: Alexandria, Virginia, Julie, and it's nice to see you again.

4
00:00:23.910 --> 00:00:37.960
Julie Stout: Nice to see you again! We are here for part two of our oral history interviews, and this one's going to specifically touch on, the Dawson Gary Project. And so, without further ado, I can jump right in, if you're all good.

5
00:00:37.960 --> 00:00:38.690
John Hasse: Sure.

6
00:00:38.690 --> 00:00:51.500
Julie Stout: Awesome. So, starting, I guess, from the beginning, I want to know more about your first involvement. How did you first become connected to the Doris and Gary project, such as, like, when, where, and in what capacity?

7
00:00:53.400 --> 00:01:00.180
John Hasse: I don't remember the exact month, but it was probably… Sometime in 1975,

8
00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:03.310
John Hasse: Because I assume it was 1975.

9
00:01:03.610 --> 00:01:09.630
John Hasse: when, Dawson would have… Submitted his application.

10
00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:13.909
John Hasse: to the National Endowment for the Humanities to fund this project.

11
00:01:14.180 --> 00:01:18.379
John Hasse: So, he probably identified the graduate students.

12
00:01:18.610 --> 00:01:21.149
John Hasse: I think we were all doctoral students.

13
00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:23.890
John Hasse: To join this project.

14
00:01:24.230 --> 00:01:26.209
John Hasse: And then the money came through, and…

15
00:01:26.380 --> 00:01:28.649
John Hasse: We went to Gary in…

16
00:01:29.930 --> 00:01:34.539
John Hasse: June of 1976. We may have started in May.

17
00:01:34.710 --> 00:01:37.129
John Hasse: And it may have gone into July?

18
00:01:37.250 --> 00:01:40.940
John Hasse: It was… I believe we were on the ground about 6 weeks.

19
00:01:43.450 --> 00:01:50.959
Julie Stout: Do you know why you were chosen for this project in particular, or why you showed interest in it, if at all?

20
00:01:52.470 --> 00:01:53.120
John Hasse: Hmm.

21
00:01:54.320 --> 00:01:58.100
John Hasse: Well, there weren't very many ethnomusicology.

22
00:01:58.240 --> 00:02:00.100
John Hasse: Doctoral students at the time.

23
00:02:00.240 --> 00:02:07.799
John Hasse: And… I think by then he knew I was interested in the music of Indiana.

24
00:02:08.210 --> 00:02:12.610
John Hasse: I was doing a lot of research on ragtime music in Indiana, which…

25
00:02:12.850 --> 00:02:15.530
John Hasse: merged into the history of jazz in Indiana.

26
00:02:15.980 --> 00:02:23.569
John Hasse: And… I'm not sure why else, but I was, happy to be involved.

27
00:02:26.290 --> 00:02:40.449
Julie Stout: When you read about the project itself, what was your initial, like, the grant proposal, if you even, like, looked at that or heard about it? What was your initial, like, thought on it? Was, like, were you intrigued by it? Were you…

28
00:02:40.770 --> 00:02:42.690
Julie Stout: Yeah, just let me know your thoughts on that.

29
00:02:43.750 --> 00:02:51.550
John Hasse: It's hard for me to… recollect or reconstruct my thoughts, but I probably was… A little surprised.

30
00:02:51.890 --> 00:02:53.750
John Hasse: And, intrigued.

31
00:02:53.940 --> 00:02:57.990
John Hasse: Because I believe he called it… the Calumet region.

32
00:02:58.260 --> 00:03:04.580
John Hasse: Which, in northwest Indiana, is simply known as the region, or some people might say colloquially.

33
00:03:04.830 --> 00:03:06.390
John Hasse: Del region.

34
00:03:06.670 --> 00:03:13.170
John Hasse: And the only… time I'd ever given any real thought to Gary was…

35
00:03:13.420 --> 00:03:19.920
John Hasse: in seeing the movie and the stage production, the Music Man, where this flim-flam,

36
00:03:20.270 --> 00:03:23.190
John Hasse: The so-called music teacher, played by Robert Preston.

37
00:03:23.610 --> 00:03:32.320
John Hasse: claimed to have a degree from the Gary Conservatory of Music in 06, which would be 2… 1906.

38
00:03:32.530 --> 00:03:35.000
John Hasse: And, I…

39
00:03:35.300 --> 00:03:42.630
John Hasse: don't know that I'd ever been through Gary, or I certainly had never stopped in Gary, so it was all gonna be a new experience to me.

40
00:03:44.820 --> 00:03:48.410
Julie Stout: But one that I'm sure you learn from immensely, correct?

41
00:03:48.650 --> 00:03:49.560
John Hasse: Oh, yes, and…

42
00:03:50.210 --> 00:03:57.650
John Hasse: About that time, I discovered the short stories of Gene, J-E-A-N, Shepherd.

43
00:03:57.810 --> 00:04:01.080
John Hasse: who was born in Hammond, Indiana, which is part of the region.

44
00:04:01.200 --> 00:04:09.630
John Hasse: It adjoins Gary, And I… absolutely loved his stories. They were… just hilarious.

45
00:04:10.340 --> 00:04:13.629
John Hasse: Based on his boyhood. And,

46
00:04:13.860 --> 00:04:18.180
John Hasse: As a matter of fact, I recommended him so strongly to Professor Dawson.

47
00:04:18.290 --> 00:04:22.829
John Hasse: That he brought him to the campus, and… A shepherd gave a…

48
00:04:23.610 --> 00:04:26.679
John Hasse: An amazing performance. It must have lasted 2 hours.

49
00:04:27.010 --> 00:04:30.100
John Hasse: Not one break, but… Not one note.

50
00:04:30.680 --> 00:04:33.739
John Hasse: He just told these stories, one after another.

51
00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:36.440
John Hasse: Everybody in the audience is spellbound.

52
00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:44.720
John Hasse: And, so that… gave Gary some context for me, even though Hammond, at that time, was…

53
00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:52.579
John Hasse: in a number of ways, different than Gary. Gary was very strongly African American.

54
00:04:52.680 --> 00:04:54.269
John Hasse: And I don't know what the…

55
00:04:54.540 --> 00:05:00.909
John Hasse: ethnic or racial makeup of Hammond was, but I don't think it was nearly as strongly black as Gary was.

56
00:05:02.340 --> 00:05:09.509
Julie Stout: So it was a little, like, like, sliver that you were able to, like, connect to in… for the area and everything, yeah.

57
00:05:09.510 --> 00:05:10.050
John Hasse: Yeah.

58
00:05:11.860 --> 00:05:27.830
Julie Stout: In speaking with other individuals and other students that were also on the project, they noted that each student had their specialty, and I know since you were… you studied ethomusicology, music was a huge thing for you, along with Richard March, who also has a music, like, background.

59
00:05:27.890 --> 00:05:38.499
Julie Stout: And I wanted to learn more about your roles and responsibilities on the project. What were your primary responsibilities, and how did they all, change, if at all, over time?

60
00:05:38.650 --> 00:05:39.290
John Hasse: Sure.

61
00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:42.620
John Hasse: Let's go back to the question about

62
00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:45.380
John Hasse: how I became involved with the project.

63
00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:47.680
John Hasse: If my chronology is correct.

64
00:05:48.460 --> 00:05:54.729
John Hasse: I had taken a fieldwork class, In the folklore department.

65
00:05:55.690 --> 00:05:58.430
John Hasse: And had decided to study.

66
00:05:58.940 --> 00:06:01.280
John Hasse: the music of a black church in Bloomington.

67
00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:03.880
John Hasse: Specifically, their gospel music.

68
00:06:04.560 --> 00:06:09.819
John Hasse: And so… It's entirely possible or probable that

69
00:06:09.930 --> 00:06:15.230
John Hasse: Dawson had heard about my fieldwork, In black gospel music, and…

70
00:06:15.530 --> 00:06:17.099
John Hasse: Brought me into the project, too.

71
00:06:17.470 --> 00:06:21.309
John Hasse: expand that fieldwork, if you would, to the northwest corner of Indiana.

72
00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:28.810
John Hasse: I don't recall receiving… very specific instructions.

73
00:06:29.050 --> 00:06:35.059
John Hasse: It's probably more like… go up to Gary, make some connections.

74
00:06:35.480 --> 00:06:40.090
John Hasse: Visit black churches, And see what you can find and document.

75
00:06:40.510 --> 00:06:43.890
John Hasse: It was pretty open-ended, as I recall.

76
00:06:44.050 --> 00:06:47.869
John Hasse: And of course, in 1976, there was no internet.

77
00:06:47.990 --> 00:06:56.620
John Hasse: There was no text messages, no mobile phones, so it was, a whole different…

78
00:06:56.930 --> 00:06:58.119
John Hasse: Kettle of fish.

79
00:06:58.430 --> 00:07:02.830
John Hasse: to, make context, I… I didn't know anybody in Gary.

80
00:07:03.400 --> 00:07:06.540
John Hasse: So I went in there.

81
00:07:06.980 --> 00:07:09.419
John Hasse: For me, it was Terra Incognita.

82
00:07:09.670 --> 00:07:14.999
John Hasse: And, what I had to do was use the phone book a lot, particularly the Yellow Pages.

83
00:07:15.120 --> 00:07:19.630
John Hasse: Looked up the section on churches, And started contacting churches.

84
00:07:20.010 --> 00:07:24.159
John Hasse: And then sometimes, certain… certain of them were dead ends.

85
00:07:24.300 --> 00:07:27.450
John Hasse: Church no longer existed, or…

86
00:07:27.710 --> 00:07:31.210
John Hasse: The phone didn't work anymore. Some churches didn't have phones.

87
00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:35.340
John Hasse: And then I got to know some people.

88
00:07:35.580 --> 00:07:37.859
John Hasse: And they pointed me to others.

89
00:07:38.580 --> 00:07:44.120
John Hasse: And, one of the others was a DJ, a long-time Gospel TJ.

90
00:07:45.020 --> 00:07:49.220
John Hasse: and the Gary radio station, Her name was Vivian Carter.

91
00:07:49.740 --> 00:07:54.830
John Hasse: And, much earlier. Well, let's see, this is 76.

92
00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:57.649
John Hasse: At least 10 years earlier.

93
00:07:58.450 --> 00:08:05.449
John Hasse: She had owned, or half-owned, I believe, VJ Records. V-E-E hyphen J-A-Y.

94
00:08:05.850 --> 00:08:08.010
John Hasse: And for a while, they… VJ…

95
00:08:08.380 --> 00:08:12.560
John Hasse: I had a license to put out a… an early Beatles LP.

96
00:08:13.660 --> 00:08:16.449
John Hasse: So she was a noted personality.

97
00:08:16.560 --> 00:08:19.120
John Hasse: And, I interviewed her, and…

98
00:08:19.500 --> 00:08:24.149
John Hasse: She pointed me in some helpful directions. Everybody was… that I…

99
00:08:24.500 --> 00:08:29.590
John Hasse: encountered was nice. I didn't meet anybody that wasn't nice to me, and I felt…

100
00:08:30.590 --> 00:08:34.190
John Hasse: Very grateful to be, Welcome, Jen.

101
00:08:34.799 --> 00:08:38.380
John Hasse: It could have been otherwise, you know, here's this…

102
00:08:38.600 --> 00:08:41.299
John Hasse: Guy was very foreign to our community.

103
00:08:41.720 --> 00:08:49.920
John Hasse: Knows very little about… The culture, and…

104
00:08:51.980 --> 00:08:57.779
John Hasse: You know, so… but people got that I was a student. Some people wondered if I was a divinity student.

105
00:08:58.700 --> 00:09:01.419
John Hasse: But they got that I was studying music, and…

106
00:09:01.590 --> 00:09:05.090
John Hasse: Just about everybody was very accepting.

107
00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:12.310
Julie Stout: Do you think your interest and knowledge of music opened doors for you into, like.

108
00:09:12.840 --> 00:09:19.289
Julie Stout: Into, like, being welcomed to, like, welcomed by this community? Or, do you think it was something else?

109
00:09:20.390 --> 00:09:21.470
John Hasse: Oh, definitely, and my bill?

110
00:09:21.470 --> 00:09:21.939
Julie Stout: What are you?

111
00:09:21.940 --> 00:09:23.969
John Hasse: To, play the piano.

112
00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:32.370
John Hasse: I'd say was… really… Important.

113
00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:39.200
John Hasse: 2… getting to know… the… gospel community.

114
00:09:39.530 --> 00:09:45.460
John Hasse: One day, I… Visited a storefront.

115
00:09:46.800 --> 00:09:48.129
John Hasse: Baptist Church.

116
00:09:49.070 --> 00:09:51.009
John Hasse: And it literally was a storefront.

117
00:09:51.780 --> 00:09:53.860
John Hasse: And the storefront windows, there were…

118
00:09:54.220 --> 00:09:56.450
John Hasse: a big mural of Mary and Joseph.

119
00:09:56.580 --> 00:10:00.490
John Hasse: Et cetera, and… Inside the… -

120
00:10:03.160 --> 00:10:04.460
John Hasse: Excuse me, store.

121
00:10:06.770 --> 00:10:08.009
John Hasse: There were about 6?

122
00:10:09.310 --> 00:10:15.020
John Hasse: Sorry, I've got a frog in my throat. Six… let me grab a little water. 6 rows of chairs, folding chairs.

123
00:10:15.250 --> 00:10:20.680
John Hasse: plain public in an Upright piano pushed up against the wall.

124
00:10:25.360 --> 00:10:33.240
John Hasse: And I… Foolishly, Brought with me a still camera, A video camera.

125
00:10:33.780 --> 00:10:35.750
John Hasse: And an audio tape recorder.

126
00:10:36.120 --> 00:10:37.430
John Hasse: Instead of all three.

127
00:10:37.670 --> 00:10:40.250
John Hasse: But the… Preacher?

128
00:10:41.100 --> 00:10:43.449
John Hasse: Had told me in advance it would be okay.

129
00:10:43.640 --> 00:10:45.819
John Hasse: To document the service in those ways.

130
00:10:46.170 --> 00:10:49.520
John Hasse: And… So about halfway through the service.

131
00:10:49.820 --> 00:10:51.770
John Hasse: He said, and we welcome today

132
00:10:52.120 --> 00:10:55.329
John Hasse: a visitor, a student from Indiana University.

133
00:10:55.510 --> 00:10:59.080
John Hasse: John Hassey, he motioned for me to stand up, and I…

134
00:10:59.340 --> 00:11:01.689
John Hasse: I didn't want any, but I wanted to be…

135
00:11:01.860 --> 00:11:09.950
John Hasse: I couldn't be inconspicuous, but I wasn't trying to be more conspicuous. I was… I felt shy and bashful and out of place.

136
00:11:10.270 --> 00:11:12.730
John Hasse: He said, could be said.

137
00:11:13.590 --> 00:11:15.320
John Hasse: You're a musician, aren't you?

138
00:11:15.770 --> 00:11:17.400
John Hasse: And I didn't say anything.

139
00:11:17.670 --> 00:11:19.280
John Hasse: How could he possibly know?

140
00:11:19.420 --> 00:11:22.490
John Hasse: And he said, You're a piano player, aren't you?

141
00:11:22.830 --> 00:11:24.909
John Hasse: And I go, no, no. He said.

142
00:11:25.030 --> 00:11:28.429
John Hasse: Come on, get up, go play us a number.

143
00:11:28.990 --> 00:11:31.129
John Hasse: I had to oblige, how could I say no?

144
00:11:31.300 --> 00:11:38.770
John Hasse: So I went over to the piano and… Gave them my interpretation of… Amazing Grace.

145
00:11:39.960 --> 00:11:50.169
John Hasse: And, I… Put in syncopations and some… Call and response cords.

146
00:11:50.610 --> 00:11:55.880
John Hasse: And it was nothing like a good… Pianist…

147
00:11:56.220 --> 00:11:59.859
John Hasse: who was a member of one of these churches could play, but, you know, I…

148
00:12:00.120 --> 00:12:03.950
John Hasse: I did the best I could, and… as I played, I was…

149
00:12:04.180 --> 00:12:07.970
John Hasse: very nervous and anxious, but I heard people,

150
00:12:08.110 --> 00:12:09.370
John Hasse: Yeah.

151
00:12:09.530 --> 00:12:14.150
John Hasse: And when I finished playing, the preachers said, Yes, hmm.

152
00:12:14.660 --> 00:12:17.190
John Hasse: People be walking by the church this morning, hear that?

153
00:12:17.340 --> 00:12:21.289
John Hasse: Good music coming out the window, and say, Nice Colored Boy playing.

154
00:12:21.870 --> 00:12:23.060
John Hasse: What's up?

155
00:12:23.450 --> 00:12:27.089
John Hasse: It was the highest compliment he could have paid me, and I…

156
00:12:27.580 --> 00:12:30.909
John Hasse: I thought about that many times after that. It was…

157
00:12:31.510 --> 00:12:35.119
John Hasse: It's so generous of him, and… affirming, and…

158
00:12:35.550 --> 00:12:38.940
John Hasse: you know, as I, as in the…

159
00:12:39.060 --> 00:12:42.160
John Hasse: black church I visited repeatedly in Bloomington.

160
00:12:43.220 --> 00:12:47.959
John Hasse: Playing the piano, made all the difference in how well I was accepted.

161
00:12:49.160 --> 00:12:53.300
John Hasse: They were… people were surprised that, you know.

162
00:12:53.490 --> 00:12:59.569
John Hasse: First of all, they were surprised to see a white guy come into their churches, in most cases, because I suspect

163
00:12:59.940 --> 00:13:03.190
John Hasse: few, if any, white people would go into these churches. Gary was…

164
00:13:03.780 --> 00:13:07.300
John Hasse: Pretty segregated, not by law, but by custom at the time.

165
00:13:07.510 --> 00:13:09.060
John Hasse: Especially in churches.

166
00:13:09.240 --> 00:13:13.370
John Hasse: One church I… visited, I interviewed the pastor.

167
00:13:13.490 --> 00:13:16.320
John Hasse: Reverend Roosevelt Rob Robinson, who is a…

168
00:13:16.510 --> 00:13:19.049
John Hasse: Full-time Teamster and a part-time pastor.

169
00:13:19.190 --> 00:13:21.669
John Hasse: This is a United Methodist Church.

170
00:13:22.090 --> 00:13:27.620
John Hasse: And he told me that One day, A 15-year-old

171
00:13:28.710 --> 00:13:31.000
John Hasse: Young man, who was black, walked in, and…

172
00:13:31.570 --> 00:13:36.149
John Hasse: 30 of the white parishioners got up and left, just like that, in the middle of the service.

173
00:13:37.240 --> 00:13:39.869
John Hasse: In the middle of the service, I asked him, he said, yes.

174
00:13:40.600 --> 00:13:41.949
John Hasse: What did you say?

175
00:13:42.330 --> 00:13:44.100
John Hasse: The preacher said, bye!

176
00:13:44.310 --> 00:13:45.729
John Hasse: What else could I say?

177
00:13:47.150 --> 00:13:48.070
John Hasse: Bye!

178
00:13:49.240 --> 00:13:52.729
John Hasse: So, I met some…

179
00:13:53.640 --> 00:13:59.100
John Hasse: memorable and wonderful people. It was a… it was a… it was a great experience. At the same time.

180
00:13:59.300 --> 00:14:04.970
John Hasse: It was personally extremely difficult for me, because Just a few weeks prior.

181
00:14:05.940 --> 00:14:11.690
John Hasse: My mother had died after a… Three-year harrowing fight against leukemia.

182
00:14:12.340 --> 00:14:15.570
John Hasse: And my father had died 5 years earlier, so…

183
00:14:15.740 --> 00:14:20.179
John Hasse: I'd lost my surviving parent, and… had no…

184
00:14:20.470 --> 00:14:23.800
John Hasse: home to go home to for the rest of my life. It was gone.

185
00:14:23.910 --> 00:14:31.650
John Hasse: So, I just plowed myself into my work in Gary, and… I… I think I worked…

186
00:14:33.590 --> 00:14:41.799
John Hasse: Seven days a week, and… was either… Talking to people, or… recording performances,

187
00:14:41.950 --> 00:14:45.980
John Hasse: Or making phone calls, you know, morning, noon, and night. There was, there was no…

188
00:14:47.160 --> 00:14:51.039
John Hasse: I allowed myself no downtime. Didn't go to one movie, didn't go to one…

189
00:14:51.290 --> 00:14:56.090
John Hasse: You know, or anything. It was just… Probably that…

190
00:14:57.770 --> 00:14:59.329
John Hasse: Help my sanity at that point.

191
00:15:02.800 --> 00:15:09.599
Julie Stout: it's… it's never easy dealing with loss of family members, but I'd like to think that

192
00:15:10.580 --> 00:15:21.130
Julie Stout: The acceptance that you felt, probably, from the community in, like, those memorable moments for something that you hold so dear to your heart, like music, it must have, like, been…

193
00:15:21.330 --> 00:15:23.230
Julie Stout: Yeah, very memorable for you.

194
00:15:23.560 --> 00:15:24.420
John Hasse: It was.

195
00:15:24.420 --> 00:15:25.150
Julie Stout: Yes.

196
00:15:26.500 --> 00:15:28.020
Julie Stout: I definitely understand that.

197
00:15:29.670 --> 00:15:30.740
Julie Stout: And…

198
00:15:32.520 --> 00:15:40.669
Julie Stout: The great… keep thinking on any of those memorable moments you might have, because there may be a question later down the line about more moments you can think of.

199
00:15:40.770 --> 00:15:44.880
Julie Stout: But, taking us back a little bit to the beginning, but…

200
00:15:45.210 --> 00:15:55.499
Julie Stout: what did you see were the project's aims at the start, and how did that evolve? Evolve either through your work or your work with Dorsen,

201
00:15:56.300 --> 00:15:58.870
Julie Stout: Yeah. How would you see the projects?

202
00:15:58.970 --> 00:16:01.850
Julie Stout: Ames evolved from the start to the end.

203
00:16:03.590 --> 00:16:04.649
John Hasse: I don't know. If I don't…

204
00:16:05.240 --> 00:16:07.310
John Hasse: I don't have a good memory of…

205
00:16:07.440 --> 00:16:08.530
Julie Stout: No worries, yeah.

206
00:16:08.760 --> 00:16:12.010
John Hasse: That, but, I…

207
00:16:15.360 --> 00:16:21.389
John Hasse: it was… From my point of view, Essentially, a documenting project.

208
00:16:21.790 --> 00:16:25.439
John Hasse: You could ask Tom Adler.

209
00:16:26.150 --> 00:16:31.340
John Hasse: and go back to Richard Marcher if you wanted, but I… I believe that, Richard…

210
00:16:31.660 --> 00:16:36.260
John Hasse: Documented, a lot of… Serbo-coration.

211
00:16:36.710 --> 00:16:40.409
John Hasse: Life in… in the… In the Hammond region.

212
00:16:41.140 --> 00:16:46.430
John Hasse: I remember… Going one time to a concert by the… Junior Tamboritsins.

213
00:16:46.550 --> 00:16:51.159
John Hasse: And helping, him video record that, and… At this,

214
00:16:52.170 --> 00:16:56.039
John Hasse: Serbian Hall, there was a very, very elderly man.

215
00:16:56.570 --> 00:17:00.030
John Hasse: Who was playing the one-string Guzla.

216
00:17:00.570 --> 00:17:02.530
John Hasse: A traditional folk instrument.

217
00:17:02.850 --> 00:17:05.420
John Hasse: And he was going on and on and on.

218
00:17:05.569 --> 00:17:09.719
John Hasse: Singing these long, epic songs. Back in Serbia.

219
00:17:10.250 --> 00:17:12.129
John Hasse: Some could go on for hours.

220
00:17:12.470 --> 00:17:19.640
John Hasse: So… maybe ancient, Type of storytelling.

221
00:17:19.890 --> 00:17:21.890
John Hasse: And all the little kids were running around.

222
00:17:23.119 --> 00:17:28.180
John Hasse: they weren't noticing him at all. I felt… I felt sorry for him, because hardly anybody was paying attention.

223
00:17:28.470 --> 00:17:32.269
John Hasse: But, to me, it was a documenting project. Now, the… the…

224
00:17:33.650 --> 00:17:35.210
John Hasse: Products that came out of it.

225
00:17:35.340 --> 00:17:37.599
John Hasse: Of course, Dawson wrote another book.

226
00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:43.119
John Hasse: He was a… good at writing and publishing books. Land of the Mill Rats.

227
00:17:43.270 --> 00:17:47.309
John Hasse: There was a special issue of Indiana Folklore, the scholarly Journal.

228
00:17:48.100 --> 00:17:53.730
John Hasse: There were articles in Folklore Forum, which was a graduate student Published.

229
00:17:54.080 --> 00:17:55.380
John Hasse: academic journal.

230
00:17:56.450 --> 00:18:01.030
John Hasse: I produced a half an hour documentary film called Gospel and Gary.

231
00:18:01.400 --> 00:18:06.789
John Hasse: And I couldn't tell you the other products, but I believe there were some as well.

232
00:18:10.660 --> 00:18:19.949
Julie Stout: Were there other collaborations between you and the other students, besides… I know you just said you were helping Richard with that specific, like, recording of the Tambrizza?

233
00:18:20.090 --> 00:18:24.849
Julie Stout: Were there any other collaborations between you or the other students? Or Dawson?

234
00:18:25.330 --> 00:18:27.610
John Hasse: Yes.

235
00:18:27.860 --> 00:18:29.950
John Hasse: Could you pause for just a moment?

236
00:18:33.700 --> 00:18:34.990
John Hasse: Or pause the recording.

237
00:18:35.500 --> 00:18:36.300
Julie Stout: Okay, good.

238
00:18:38.430 --> 00:18:46.770
John Hasse: There was a, another member of the so-called Gary Gang, Adrian Seward, A lovely, a lovely lady.

239
00:18:46.990 --> 00:18:51.409
John Hasse: and we worked together a little bit. She helped me record…

240
00:18:51.720 --> 00:18:55.769
John Hasse: Video record some of the, gospel performances, so…

241
00:18:55.960 --> 00:19:00.170
John Hasse: She is credited as, one of the camera people.

242
00:19:00.810 --> 00:19:03.550
John Hasse: At the end of that, half-hour video.

243
00:19:05.280 --> 00:19:11.649
Julie Stout: Did she also have a music background, or was it just, like, passing interest, or how did that even come up?

244
00:19:12.160 --> 00:19:18.200
John Hasse: I don't think… I don't remember if she had a music background, but she was on the folklore track.

245
00:19:18.390 --> 00:19:26.619
John Hasse: And I was on the ethnomusicology track, and… I, got the money.

246
00:19:27.010 --> 00:19:30.469
John Hasse: To hire a helicopter pilot in a helicopter.

247
00:19:30.760 --> 00:19:33.680
John Hasse: And we went up over the city of Gary.

248
00:19:34.010 --> 00:19:39.700
John Hasse: And I had my little Sony… portable camera.

249
00:19:40.210 --> 00:19:41.030
John Hasse: Shot.

250
00:19:41.220 --> 00:19:42.470
John Hasse: In black and white.

251
00:19:43.010 --> 00:19:44.780
John Hasse: Because the tape was all black and white.

252
00:19:45.140 --> 00:19:52.129
John Hasse: shot some, aerial views of Gary, and that… Begins the, the documentary video.

253
00:19:53.540 --> 00:20:03.100
Julie Stout: A helicopter! Wow! That's awesome to, you were able to get those shots to start off your documentary and everything.

254
00:20:03.490 --> 00:20:06.359
John Hasse: One of the most memorable things

255
00:20:06.600 --> 00:20:09.500
John Hasse: was, Dawson took us to…

256
00:20:09.650 --> 00:20:12.250
John Hasse: a plant of United States steel.

257
00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:14.889
John Hasse: a U.S. steel mill or plant.

258
00:20:15.380 --> 00:20:24.009
John Hasse: And, we went down, down, down in an elevator, and then we walked sideways, And there was…

259
00:20:24.580 --> 00:20:29.080
John Hasse: There were big blast furnaces. I mean, these were enormous.

260
00:20:29.710 --> 00:20:36.160
John Hasse: If memory serves, they were… Maybe 15, 20 feet wide.

261
00:20:36.730 --> 00:20:41.679
John Hasse: And… The door to one of them was opened, and you looked inside, and it was just…

262
00:20:41.820 --> 00:20:47.290
John Hasse: Red-hot fire, just… ablaze in there, I mean, just burning, burning. You could feel the heat.

263
00:20:47.530 --> 00:20:49.160
John Hasse: 15, 20 feet back.

264
00:20:49.600 --> 00:20:52.840
John Hasse: I mean, Isthma's… I wrote in a journal.

265
00:20:53.320 --> 00:20:59.490
John Hasse: about it, said, this is a fiery vision of hell. It was… I'll never forget that.

266
00:21:01.540 --> 00:21:13.089
Julie Stout: Did he take you students to that place to show… to show you more of, like, Gary itself, and, like, the infrastructure, or was it just, like, a field trip, per se, would you say?

267
00:21:14.700 --> 00:21:16.680
John Hasse: Well, he thought we would benefit from.

268
00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:17.720
Julie Stout: From seeing it.

269
00:21:18.010 --> 00:21:21.480
John Hasse: The work that so many of our informants did.

270
00:21:21.920 --> 00:21:25.139
John Hasse: Because that was the number one employer.

271
00:21:25.440 --> 00:21:28.460
John Hasse: in Gary, and possibly the surrounding towns.

272
00:21:28.620 --> 00:21:38.900
John Hasse: And, the mills, You could say, dominated the skyline, they dominated the economy, and they dominated employment.

273
00:21:44.170 --> 00:21:53.330
Julie Stout: Did you take any footage of that, or was it mostly just to see it up close and personal to understand?

274
00:21:54.320 --> 00:21:56.669
John Hasse: I don't recall taking any footage.

275
00:21:57.380 --> 00:22:06.360
John Hasse: I had, and if I had… Still photos, they're long forgotten, but, maybe you'll be able to…

276
00:22:06.600 --> 00:22:13.559
John Hasse: Cracked down all this, because it was, just an incredible treasure of…

277
00:22:14.240 --> 00:22:17.710
John Hasse: Performances and interviews and, images.

278
00:22:20.140 --> 00:22:28.279
Julie Stout: Did you record and take pictures and interview under the impression that this would be archived in the future, or was it…

279
00:22:28.430 --> 00:22:30.530
Julie Stout: Did you know what the end goal was?

280
00:22:31.320 --> 00:22:32.189
Julie Stout: From your work.

281
00:22:32.190 --> 00:22:33.889
John Hasse: It's going to deposit all my…

282
00:22:34.540 --> 00:22:35.680
John Hasse: documentation.

283
00:22:36.450 --> 00:22:43.350
John Hasse: at IU, and so that was… that was my goal, to get… Is…

284
00:22:43.450 --> 00:22:45.759
John Hasse: complete a picture as I could, given

285
00:22:46.760 --> 00:22:48.630
John Hasse: I got there not knowing anybody.

286
00:22:48.980 --> 00:22:51.670
John Hasse: And we had only so many days in Gary.

287
00:22:52.330 --> 00:22:53.800
John Hasse: In the surrounding region.

288
00:22:54.750 --> 00:22:59.460
John Hasse: To get as much… Captured, documented.

289
00:22:59.700 --> 00:23:03.719
John Hasse: as I could, and then… It would be saved for posterity at IU.

290
00:23:05.380 --> 00:23:12.029
Julie Stout: And here it is, still today, at IU and other campuses, even. People are still able to view them.

291
00:23:13.450 --> 00:23:28.529
Julie Stout: So, I know you mentioned your memorable experiences and interviews you've had with people. I wanted to ask you a quick question about ethics and consent, which this is more of a modern thing that's come up in the past, decades or so, but…

292
00:23:28.560 --> 00:23:34.169
Julie Stout: When you were, like, discussing or talking with your informants and other individuals.

293
00:23:34.460 --> 00:23:45.140
Julie Stout: How were ethical considerations, like, handled, if at all? Like, were there, did you need permissions or confidentiality, with the people that you talked to?

294
00:23:46.580 --> 00:23:49.040
John Hasse: I don't believe anybody told me anything.

295
00:23:49.200 --> 00:23:50.620
John Hasse: That was confidential.

296
00:23:51.220 --> 00:23:55.600
John Hasse: The closest to confidential I came was

297
00:23:56.240 --> 00:23:59.209
John Hasse: I was invited to join a prayer meeting.

298
00:23:59.450 --> 00:24:01.540
John Hasse: when… Late afternoon.

299
00:24:01.840 --> 00:24:02.860
John Hasse: Or evening.

300
00:24:04.040 --> 00:24:05.799
John Hasse: In one of the black churches.

301
00:24:05.980 --> 00:24:12.130
John Hasse: And I had never… been to a prayer meeting. I was raised Methodist, then Unitarian.

302
00:24:13.520 --> 00:24:16.890
John Hasse: And I'd never been to a permeating, I'd never even heard of a permeating.

303
00:24:17.090 --> 00:24:23.540
John Hasse: But, they were about… 15… People mostly… women.

304
00:24:24.400 --> 00:24:29.340
John Hasse: We sat down on the floor, Very ragged circle.

305
00:24:30.280 --> 00:24:36.640
John Hasse: And… After some prompt from the preacher, People begin praying.

306
00:24:36.840 --> 00:24:37.770
John Hasse: Oh, wow.

307
00:24:38.410 --> 00:24:44.000
John Hasse: And… Help my herman. Thank you, Jesus.

308
00:24:44.210 --> 00:24:48.830
John Hasse: Things like that, and I didn't follow up.

309
00:24:48.970 --> 00:24:53.489
John Hasse: the parishioners… with any questions, because I thought that would have been prying.

310
00:24:53.800 --> 00:24:58.570
John Hasse: I wasn't going to put them on the spot, or make them feel uncomfortable, or anything like that.

311
00:24:58.910 --> 00:25:07.010
John Hasse: But, no, I don't recall that, Dawson Talked with us about… Ethics.

312
00:25:07.380 --> 00:25:13.819
John Hasse: Or… As one would today, getting permission.

313
00:25:14.210 --> 00:25:22.810
John Hasse: The others… said they didn't get permission, and then I didn't. I don't recall.

314
00:25:23.570 --> 00:25:27.110
John Hasse: having to get permission. I mean, today, of course, wouldn't dream of…

315
00:25:27.420 --> 00:25:31.460
John Hasse: Recording somebody without permission, but back then, that was… That was a different time.

316
00:25:33.280 --> 00:25:38.619
Julie Stout: Which is why I thought of it as a question to ask, because I was curious to know

317
00:25:38.720 --> 00:25:54.670
Julie Stout: if the project did handle it in a way that we would consider, like, ethical, or, what other ways was it handled? So… and no other student that I've talked to so far has said they needed, like, written permission or anything like that, similar to you.

318
00:25:54.670 --> 00:26:01.350
John Hasse: a… it wasn't… That we were being unethical. It was that this…

319
00:26:02.060 --> 00:26:03.739
John Hasse: Wasn't an issue at the time.

320
00:26:04.050 --> 00:26:11.960
John Hasse: Field workers, generally used to ask people if they'd Sit for an interview, or… There we go.

321
00:26:12.160 --> 00:26:17.049
John Hasse: Performance could be… recorded, and… It was much less…

322
00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:19.220
John Hasse: What did you time back then?

323
00:26:21.100 --> 00:26:22.470
Julie Stout: I definitely understand.

324
00:26:24.350 --> 00:26:40.710
Julie Stout: This might feed into your own stories and anecdotes, but I was wondering if you experienced any quote-unquote pivotal events or decisions that shaped the project's direction, or your own, outlook on how you want to conduct fieldwork and document the community.

325
00:26:42.020 --> 00:26:42.670
John Hasse: Hmm.

326
00:26:45.940 --> 00:26:50.069
John Hasse: You know, if I hadn't… Taken that course in field work.

327
00:26:50.550 --> 00:26:55.579
John Hasse: And I believe it was from Henry Classy, the… legendary folklorist at IU.

328
00:26:56.120 --> 00:27:00.909
John Hasse: I don't think I would have been selected.

329
00:27:01.940 --> 00:27:03.940
John Hasse: Join the so-called Gary Game.

330
00:27:04.460 --> 00:27:11.230
John Hasse: And so that was… that was a very formative experience when I… Tiptoed into this,

331
00:27:11.950 --> 00:27:13.819
John Hasse: church on the west side of Bloomington.

332
00:27:14.460 --> 00:27:21.700
John Hasse: I was feeling so shy and conspicuous, and I just kind of tried to shrink down my body, and I…

333
00:27:21.850 --> 00:27:24.579
John Hasse: Tiptoed in and sat down in the back row.

334
00:27:24.850 --> 00:27:28.480
John Hasse: there may be… 10 rows of, church pews.

335
00:27:29.410 --> 00:27:31.469
John Hasse: Is the only white person in the church.

336
00:27:32.990 --> 00:27:36.249
John Hasse: I sat down, Kind of trying to hunch down.

337
00:27:36.540 --> 00:27:41.359
John Hasse: And the preacher, I, Tall, stout woman,

338
00:27:43.210 --> 00:27:46.760
John Hasse: saw me immediately. I wasn't fooling her or anybody else, she said.

339
00:27:47.020 --> 00:27:51.239
John Hasse: Come on out front, brother. The back row is for the back sliders.

340
00:27:51.550 --> 00:27:56.070
John Hasse: So… So… No.

341
00:27:58.030 --> 00:28:00.009
John Hasse: No choice but to comply.

342
00:28:00.170 --> 00:28:08.360
John Hasse: I went up to the front row, and, afterwards,

343
00:28:09.130 --> 00:28:13.770
John Hasse: Some of the congregants gathered in a circle, And…

344
00:28:14.230 --> 00:28:16.960
John Hasse: Began praying, and then speaking in tongues.

345
00:28:17.650 --> 00:28:21.000
John Hasse: And I'd never… Experienced? Witnessed?

346
00:28:21.300 --> 00:28:22.470
John Hasse: Anything like that.

347
00:28:23.130 --> 00:28:26.859
John Hasse: To my great surprise, After a while?

348
00:28:29.580 --> 00:28:31.310
John Hasse: I was speaking in tongues, too.

349
00:28:32.110 --> 00:28:34.839
John Hasse: And… I don't know whether it was,

350
00:28:36.430 --> 00:28:38.499
John Hasse: The Spirit got hold of me, or…

351
00:28:39.980 --> 00:28:48.060
John Hasse: I was just… unintentionally following the example of the people around me. It never happened again.

352
00:28:48.490 --> 00:28:53.430
John Hasse: But it was, these experiences at this church.

353
00:28:54.530 --> 00:28:58.079
John Hasse: we're really… formative. They asked me to…

354
00:28:58.180 --> 00:28:59.869
John Hasse: play the piano, and I did, they…

355
00:29:00.070 --> 00:29:01.619
John Hasse: Even though I didn't think I was…

356
00:29:02.310 --> 00:29:10.909
John Hasse: Very good at all. They said, well, you're the best pianists we've ever had. Would you please accompany the choir every Sunday? We have a radio broadcast.

357
00:29:11.290 --> 00:29:16.260
John Hasse: And… you know, I was so… Honored when she asked me.

358
00:29:17.010 --> 00:29:21.440
John Hasse: But, tell you.

359
00:29:21.700 --> 00:29:23.670
John Hasse: The work is just piled on.

360
00:29:25.060 --> 00:29:30.620
John Hasse: graduate students, at the time, and I, I… I… I couldn't…

361
00:29:30.740 --> 00:29:34.460
John Hasse: I couldn't make the time, so I had to… Politely thank her and decline.

362
00:29:35.030 --> 00:29:39.660
John Hasse: But those were… those were the formative experiences that set me up for the 6 weeks in Gary.

363
00:29:42.020 --> 00:29:48.610
Julie Stout: Are there any other, stories or anecdotes you'd like to share of your time, doing the work?

364
00:29:48.720 --> 00:29:50.129
Julie Stout: For the Gary Project.

365
00:29:50.600 --> 00:29:51.500
John Hasse: Hmm…

366
00:29:51.500 --> 00:29:53.030
Julie Stout: Anything that comes to mind?

367
00:29:55.140 --> 00:29:59.740
John Hasse: It was a corny joke, you'd call it a dad joke, that… Richard Dawson told.

368
00:30:00.200 --> 00:30:05.030
John Hasse: after, I think after we were there, maybe it was during the time we were there, that

369
00:30:06.520 --> 00:30:07.870
John Hasse: Joe worked.

370
00:30:08.240 --> 00:30:10.780
John Hasse: many, many years at the U.S. Steel Plant.

371
00:30:11.890 --> 00:30:20.109
John Hasse: And finally, his… 65th… 65th birthday came around, and… He had to retire.

372
00:30:20.650 --> 00:30:25.030
John Hasse: Every day when Joe left the… plant.

373
00:30:25.340 --> 00:30:29.770
John Hasse: The guard stopped him because Joe was pushing a covered wheelbarrow.

374
00:30:30.120 --> 00:30:35.190
John Hasse: And every day, The guard lifted the tarp and looked inside.

375
00:30:35.560 --> 00:30:36.719
John Hasse: And it was empty.

376
00:30:38.330 --> 00:30:40.289
John Hasse: Day after day, day after day.

377
00:30:40.740 --> 00:30:42.380
John Hasse: Wheelbarrow was always empty.

378
00:30:42.710 --> 00:30:47.379
John Hasse: And so finally, on Joe's last day, the guard says, Hey, Joe.

379
00:30:47.800 --> 00:30:52.120
John Hasse: Every day you've been going out here with a wheelbarrow, and I look inside, there's nothing in it.

380
00:30:53.010 --> 00:30:56.600
John Hasse: What have you been stealing? And Joe says, Wheelbarrows.

381
00:31:00.750 --> 00:31:06.019
John Hasse: So, that's one thing I remember about Dawson, and… I remember one night.

382
00:31:07.060 --> 00:31:11.200
John Hasse: I think we were on the campus of… Indiana University Northwest.

383
00:31:11.710 --> 00:31:16.169
John Hasse: And… We had to go from…

384
00:31:17.550 --> 00:31:21.690
John Hasse: cars to a building, or from one building to the other. I just remember it was a…

385
00:31:22.310 --> 00:31:23.979
John Hasse: Partially moonlit night.

386
00:31:24.180 --> 00:31:25.729
John Hasse: Probably 9 o'clock at night.

387
00:31:26.950 --> 00:31:28.100
John Hasse: Mostly dark.

388
00:31:28.740 --> 00:31:31.330
John Hasse: And… Dawson started running.

389
00:31:31.910 --> 00:31:35.129
John Hasse: And… You know, he wasn't in great shape.

390
00:31:35.510 --> 00:31:37.970
John Hasse: And he had lots of heart problems.

391
00:31:38.710 --> 00:31:41.779
John Hasse: His tongue was practically hanging out of his mouth like a…

392
00:31:42.010 --> 00:31:44.759
John Hasse: Like a, tired dog might do.

393
00:31:45.030 --> 00:31:50.109
John Hasse: And I remember being really worried that Grief, should he be running?

394
00:31:50.850 --> 00:31:52.359
John Hasse: You could get another heart attack.

395
00:31:53.020 --> 00:32:02.800
John Hasse: He was a man who… Almost single-handedly made folklore a respected, academic discipline.

396
00:32:03.690 --> 00:32:09.560
John Hasse: And, did much… Much for the discipline. He was also the… Chair of…

397
00:32:10.700 --> 00:32:13.700
John Hasse: I don't know the number, but it could have been over a hundred.

398
00:32:14.330 --> 00:32:25.840
John Hasse: doctoral dissertations at Indiana University. He always wanted to be the chair of the committee, even though it wasn't his area of expertise. So, he was the chair of my committee, which had to do with ragtime, which he knew nothing about.

399
00:32:26.110 --> 00:32:29.740
John Hasse: The advisor was Ruth Stone, the ethnomusicologist.

400
00:32:29.850 --> 00:32:35.150
John Hasse: But, I remember he pushed himself so hard.

401
00:32:35.540 --> 00:32:37.630
John Hasse: It is writing.

402
00:32:37.770 --> 00:32:41.739
John Hasse: And during the Gary project, I saw more examples of that.

403
00:32:42.450 --> 00:32:44.980
John Hasse: And I had to feel sorry for his wife.

404
00:32:45.840 --> 00:32:48.110
John Hasse: I suspect she was long-suffering, that…

405
00:32:50.380 --> 00:32:55.929
John Hasse: Long hours at the office, probably worked all weekend on his next book, whatever it was.

406
00:32:57.070 --> 00:33:08.320
John Hasse: And… I learned from that. I learned that, you know, You can have… A great career, You can have…

407
00:33:08.980 --> 00:33:15.920
John Hasse: Great health, And you can have… a great… Marriage, relationship.

408
00:33:16.690 --> 00:33:20.009
John Hasse: But it's very, very, very difficult to have all three.

409
00:33:20.760 --> 00:33:26.480
John Hasse: And I suspect, in Dawson's case, The work came first, and…

410
00:33:29.690 --> 00:33:30.570
John Hasse: Marriage.

411
00:33:31.510 --> 00:33:36.320
John Hasse: wasn't that important, and I don't… I didn't see any evidence that he took care of himself by…

412
00:33:37.130 --> 00:33:39.930
John Hasse: going to the gym or anything, so I worried about him, and…

413
00:33:41.190 --> 00:33:44.699
John Hasse: A couple years after I left IU, in fact, he did pass away.

414
00:33:45.140 --> 00:33:46.720
John Hasse: I'm guessing of a heart attack.

415
00:33:47.450 --> 00:33:53.890
John Hasse: So that was, he was a… he was a positive example in many ways for lots of

416
00:33:54.860 --> 00:33:58.789
John Hasse: aspiring scholars, but this was one way in which I felt

417
00:33:59.070 --> 00:34:01.910
John Hasse: At least for me, he was a negative example.

418
00:34:03.650 --> 00:34:08.199
Julie Stout: And you saw that firsthand working with him on this project, I'm sure.

419
00:34:08.690 --> 00:34:09.510
Julie Stout: Yeah.

420
00:34:11.710 --> 00:34:16.739
Julie Stout: Are there any other anecdotes you'd like to share before I move on to this next question?

421
00:34:17.080 --> 00:34:22.970
John Hasse: Hmm… Nothing leaps to mind, Julie, but,

422
00:34:24.020 --> 00:34:25.589
John Hasse: Think in the back of my brain about it.

423
00:34:25.590 --> 00:34:34.779
Julie Stout: just think at the back of your brain, while I keep… I only have a few more here for this section, so no worries to keep thinking.

424
00:34:35.690 --> 00:34:47.070
Julie Stout: This one's kind of an interesting one, but which materials, whether that be photos or recordings or documents, would you highlight for preservation? And where do you know that they are housed, if you do know?

425
00:34:49.620 --> 00:34:55.159
John Hasse: Well, I took, dozens of rolls of film.

426
00:34:56.909 --> 00:34:59.550
John Hasse: I think they're mostly black and white.

427
00:34:59.960 --> 00:35:01.669
John Hasse: They were all 35mm.

428
00:35:02.770 --> 00:35:04.509
John Hasse: There were some color.

429
00:35:04.630 --> 00:35:05.510
John Hasse: Pictures.

430
00:35:06.120 --> 00:35:09.120
John Hasse: Because I have a color snapshot.

431
00:35:09.610 --> 00:35:16.500
John Hasse: A group of steelworkers, Gathered on a weekend on a street corner, Singing Dua.

432
00:35:16.890 --> 00:35:18.280
John Hasse: Unaccompanied doo-op.

433
00:35:18.820 --> 00:35:20.680
John Hasse: So there were some color photos.

434
00:35:21.420 --> 00:35:30.190
John Hasse: And… I took, I shot dozens of videotapes.

435
00:35:30.990 --> 00:35:33.229
John Hasse: And dozens of audio tapes.

436
00:35:34.220 --> 00:35:42.880
John Hasse: And… I don't have the details in front of me, but… I'm very concerned that,

437
00:35:42.990 --> 00:35:47.620
John Hasse: And I tried to track some of these down a couple years ago, Nobody could find them.

438
00:35:48.680 --> 00:35:54.480
John Hasse: And I'm very, very worried that this material, that somebody… Threw it out.

439
00:35:56.070 --> 00:36:01.569
John Hasse: I hope that's not the case, but I was so incensed, I was ready to write the president of the university.

440
00:36:01.960 --> 00:36:05.640
John Hasse: I still might. I don't know. I just can't understand why.

441
00:36:06.590 --> 00:36:07.850
John Hasse: Why it can't be found.

442
00:36:11.370 --> 00:36:16.579
Julie Stout: And that was to deposit them to IU Bloomington, and not Northwest, correct?

443
00:36:16.780 --> 00:36:17.330
John Hasse: Right.

444
00:36:17.520 --> 00:36:17.900
Julie Stout: Right.

445
00:36:18.210 --> 00:36:22.550
John Hasse: If memory serves, and it might not… In this case.

446
00:36:23.050 --> 00:36:26.110
John Hasse: the… videotapes…

447
00:36:31.110 --> 00:36:33.860
John Hasse: were at the Folklore Institute.

448
00:36:34.530 --> 00:36:38.150
John Hasse: And the audio tapes went to the archives of traditional music.

449
00:36:38.550 --> 00:36:46.680
John Hasse: I've forgotten where the… photograph, negatives and slides went probably to the Folklore Institute as well.

450
00:36:47.700 --> 00:36:52.830
Julie Stout: Those, I think… I remember some of your photographs being in IU Archives.

451
00:36:53.160 --> 00:36:58.859
Julie Stout: at this point, but I'm currently working through Archives of Traditional Music videos.

452
00:36:59.250 --> 00:37:09.250
Julie Stout: And so, I can also let you know if I find them. Because at this… up to the point where I was inquiring about them, they had not been described or published or anything, and so…

453
00:37:09.630 --> 00:37:17.820
Julie Stout: I'm the one describing and publishing them. And so, if I see anything, I can let you know for sure.

454
00:37:18.020 --> 00:37:19.020
John Hasse: Thank you very much.

455
00:37:19.390 --> 00:37:23.159
Julie Stout: But you, yeah, you put many hours into your work, and…

456
00:37:23.570 --> 00:37:32.070
Julie Stout: took great care in trying to make sure that you did it justice, and so I understand why you would want it to be… to know where it's housed currently, so…

457
00:37:32.270 --> 00:37:33.060
Julie Stout: Yeah.

458
00:37:33.550 --> 00:37:34.859
Julie Stout: I definitely understand.

459
00:37:37.160 --> 00:37:51.960
Julie Stout: Okay, this one's kind of… this next question feeds into what you mentioned before, because I know Richard and Richard March and Inta Carpenter touch heavily on the struggles with, the technology.

460
00:37:52.160 --> 00:38:11.800
Julie Stout: the video cameras, the, this giant equipment, giant heavy equipment that none of you guys have worked with before, presumably. And maybe this is the same for you, but what was your biggest challenge, and toughest hurdles to overcome, and how were they addressed?

461
00:38:15.510 --> 00:38:18.289
John Hasse: Well, I'd had some experience with these still cameras.

462
00:38:19.220 --> 00:38:22.580
John Hasse: And some experience with a… portable.

463
00:38:22.950 --> 00:38:26.099
John Hasse: high quality, Audio tape recorder.

464
00:38:26.220 --> 00:38:27.260
John Hasse: Reel to reel.

465
00:38:29.280 --> 00:38:36.219
John Hasse: the two… brands that… If the musicologists would use in the field were…

466
00:38:36.410 --> 00:38:39.890
John Hasse: At that time, I believe, Nagra, N-A-G-R-A.

467
00:38:40.310 --> 00:38:43.900
John Hasse: or UHER, U-H-E-R, which is probably a…

468
00:38:44.350 --> 00:38:46.889
John Hasse: German, but could have been a Swiss or Austrian company.

469
00:38:48.660 --> 00:38:49.380
John Hasse: I think.

470
00:38:50.090 --> 00:38:57.550
John Hasse: We had a… Here. Nagas were more expensive, but, marvelous technology for the time.

471
00:38:58.350 --> 00:39:01.820
John Hasse: The video camera was a challenge.

472
00:39:02.290 --> 00:39:04.780
John Hasse: And it was clunky.

473
00:39:04.890 --> 00:39:07.350
John Hasse: It's shot only in black and white, the tape was…

474
00:39:09.270 --> 00:39:14.870
John Hasse: Maybe it was an inch wide, it was a… A format that's long since Gone obsolete.

475
00:39:15.760 --> 00:39:17.880
John Hasse: And it didn't always work.

476
00:39:18.610 --> 00:39:21.560
John Hasse: It was also kind of heavy, and lugging.

477
00:39:22.430 --> 00:39:24.220
John Hasse: These three things around.

478
00:39:24.630 --> 00:39:32.130
John Hasse: At the same time, was a lot. It was very awkward and heavy, and… Fragile.

479
00:39:32.640 --> 00:39:37.440
John Hasse: So that was… that was just the bulk and, weight of them.

480
00:39:38.170 --> 00:39:39.530
John Hasse: Presented a challenge.

481
00:39:43.790 --> 00:39:45.390
Julie Stout: Any other… oh, sorry.

482
00:39:45.390 --> 00:39:49.539
John Hasse: Yeah, sorry. The editing of the videotape was another challenge. I mean,

483
00:39:50.980 --> 00:39:56.740
John Hasse: I had worked in the archives of traditional music as a… research assistant.

484
00:39:57.870 --> 00:40:02.800
John Hasse: And I learned how to… Edit and splice audio tape.

485
00:40:03.730 --> 00:40:06.530
John Hasse: Back then, we had a razor blade, a little cutting block.

486
00:40:06.970 --> 00:40:10.199
John Hasse: You make a diagonal cut in the tape.

487
00:40:10.410 --> 00:40:18.040
John Hasse: And then you… we had some adhesive tape that would tape the two… pieces of… Videotaped together.

488
00:40:20.430 --> 00:40:22.849
John Hasse: You couldn't do that with the videotape.

489
00:40:25.030 --> 00:40:28.460
John Hasse: And so… I don't recall.

490
00:40:29.140 --> 00:40:34.210
John Hasse: exactly how I managed to make this 30-minute documentary, because it had

491
00:40:36.840 --> 00:40:44.689
John Hasse: 8, 10 different clips in it, and… As I recall, it's fairly… continuous, there's not…

492
00:40:45.360 --> 00:40:48.780
John Hasse: 5 seconds of dead screen between the various segments.

493
00:40:49.290 --> 00:40:52.639
John Hasse: But it was… it was not easy, that's for sure.

494
00:40:54.470 --> 00:41:00.619
Julie Stout: The technology continues to be one of the biggest things that the students have said that they struggled with.

495
00:41:00.800 --> 00:41:06.380
Julie Stout: Was there anything else that comes to mind for any challenges that you had to overcome through your time?

496
00:41:07.640 --> 00:41:14.469
John Hasse: Oh, well, I've touched on, the… incredible loss I was feeling.

497
00:41:16.150 --> 00:41:24.630
John Hasse: Because of the death of my mother, I would say, Fatigue,

498
00:41:25.490 --> 00:41:35.640
John Hasse: Man, I could have used some downtime then, I… I mean… I, you know, if… If a, wise.

499
00:41:35.820 --> 00:41:38.990
John Hasse: Man, or a… excellent,

500
00:41:41.080 --> 00:41:46.349
John Hasse: psychotherapist could have come into my life at that time, told me what to do, I'm sure they would have said.

501
00:41:46.610 --> 00:41:51.250
John Hasse: John, you need some downtime. You've been through a… Traumatic loss.

502
00:41:51.420 --> 00:41:53.790
John Hasse: And, you just need to…

503
00:41:53.910 --> 00:41:56.179
John Hasse: Time for yourself to start healing.

504
00:41:56.330 --> 00:41:58.779
John Hasse: And I didn't get that at all.

505
00:41:59.840 --> 00:42:01.040
John Hasse: with the Gary Project.

506
00:42:05.250 --> 00:42:10.440
John Hasse: It was a challenge constantly, because I was constantly doing Unfamiliar, new things.

507
00:42:10.670 --> 00:42:13.279
John Hasse: you know, Gary and the surrounding area was totally…

508
00:42:13.560 --> 00:42:17.410
John Hasse: new to me, Terra Incognita, as I said, and…

509
00:42:17.970 --> 00:42:22.279
John Hasse: I have to improvise constantly. What do I say to this preacher?

510
00:42:22.490 --> 00:42:24.729
John Hasse: how do I approach this singing group, you know?

511
00:42:26.890 --> 00:42:29.840
John Hasse: Where should I set up my mic? Where should I set up the camera?

512
00:42:30.290 --> 00:42:31.810
John Hasse: How long should I stay?

513
00:42:33.500 --> 00:42:37.339
John Hasse: Is there anything I can do to help these folks who've been helpful to me?

514
00:42:37.980 --> 00:42:46.809
John Hasse: if the project were today, I would think that the… Director would have.

515
00:42:46.980 --> 00:42:48.939
John Hasse: asked the NEH.

516
00:42:49.320 --> 00:42:52.230
John Hasse: For money to compensate the informants.

517
00:42:52.780 --> 00:42:57.270
John Hasse: Because some of these people were taking time off from their work.

518
00:42:57.470 --> 00:43:00.439
John Hasse: They could be rehearsing, they could have been doing a gig, perhaps.

519
00:43:00.860 --> 00:43:04.650
John Hasse: And I felt bad at the time that we had no money to give anybody.

520
00:43:05.330 --> 00:43:09.140
John Hasse: And there was a… a group of…

521
00:43:10.630 --> 00:43:12.190
John Hasse: I think it was 4 singers.

522
00:43:15.110 --> 00:43:17.960
John Hasse: And they model themselves after

523
00:43:24.840 --> 00:43:26.160
John Hasse: The Barrett sisters.

524
00:43:26.580 --> 00:43:30.180
John Hasse: And they sang a couple songs for me, and I recorded it.

525
00:43:30.570 --> 00:43:32.819
John Hasse: And then… I heard what I'm saying.

526
00:43:33.500 --> 00:43:36.450
John Hasse: Not to me, but to the other ones. That's enough.

527
00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:40.160
John Hasse: Like, you know… We shouldn't be giving our way… our…

528
00:43:41.510 --> 00:43:47.680
John Hasse: Art and our music without compensation, and… I felt bad again.

529
00:43:47.780 --> 00:43:51.080
John Hasse: But that wasn't… part of the project, I had…

530
00:43:51.280 --> 00:43:52.850
John Hasse: Not a penny to give anybody.

531
00:43:56.910 --> 00:44:02.650
Julie Stout: I think that also feeds into, like, maybe ethical considerations as well, in terms of…

532
00:44:03.260 --> 00:44:13.280
Julie Stout: understand that people are giving their time, their effort, and, experiences and voice to you as well. And so, I think it feeds into that.

533
00:44:14.160 --> 00:44:21.800
John Hasse: Yeah, and… The next time, I had an opportunity.

534
00:44:22.730 --> 00:44:28.949
John Hasse: to… Set up the rules for an oral history project.

535
00:44:29.660 --> 00:44:35.030
John Hasse: Which was… In about 1990, when I was at the Smithsonian.

536
00:44:35.970 --> 00:44:40.980
John Hasse: we re-established the Smithsonian Jazz Oral History Project, or program.

537
00:44:41.860 --> 00:44:43.289
John Hasse: And I insisted.

538
00:44:43.580 --> 00:44:49.220
John Hasse: That we not only compensate the interviewers, But the interviewees.

539
00:44:49.660 --> 00:44:55.250
John Hasse: Because these people were tradition bearers, very valuable with all the knowledge and experience.

540
00:44:55.780 --> 00:44:57.520
John Hasse: Wisdom they have to share.

541
00:44:57.900 --> 00:45:01.550
John Hasse: And… Their time was at least as valuable as the…

542
00:45:02.120 --> 00:45:05.000
John Hasse: Scholars and writers we hired to do the interviews.

543
00:45:05.320 --> 00:45:16.990
John Hasse: And so we… calculated the… the, price… Or the income that, Professional jazz musician.

544
00:45:17.310 --> 00:45:19.870
John Hasse: Would make, in, say, 3 or 4 hour period.

545
00:45:20.500 --> 00:45:25.690
John Hasse: as if they were doing a gig, and that's what we offered them, and I felt… Very good about.

546
00:45:29.510 --> 00:45:32.570
Julie Stout: I think it's interesting that you kind of,

547
00:45:33.060 --> 00:45:46.049
Julie Stout: just mention, I'm like, what would you do now? And I think that feeds in, like, wonderfully into how you were able to actually compensate people in your own project in the future, and keep that in mind, and for consideration as well.

548
00:45:46.920 --> 00:45:54.250
Julie Stout: Did you get anything as a graduate student from this? Was this part of your, like, appointment, or was it, like, a part-time thing, or…

549
00:45:55.820 --> 00:45:58.669
John Hasse: I don't think I've got any academic credit.

550
00:45:58.990 --> 00:45:59.670
Julie Stout: Right.

551
00:46:00.960 --> 00:46:04.569
John Hasse: Certainly, our expenses paid,

552
00:46:05.840 --> 00:46:08.180
John Hasse: We stayed at the red… in.

553
00:46:08.420 --> 00:46:10.730
John Hasse: in Merrillville, Indiana.

554
00:46:10.960 --> 00:46:14.240
John Hasse: It was, pretty low budget.

555
00:46:15.230 --> 00:46:18.899
John Hasse: But it was convenient. I think most of us were there.

556
00:46:19.550 --> 00:46:22.959
John Hasse: So, our expenses were paid.

557
00:46:23.240 --> 00:46:26.520
John Hasse: And we must have gotten some kind of stipend. I mean, nothing…

558
00:46:26.650 --> 00:46:30.449
John Hasse: We could get rich on, or even pay a semester's tuition with, but…

559
00:46:30.670 --> 00:46:32.510
John Hasse: There must have been some kind of stipend.

560
00:46:34.520 --> 00:46:40.420
Julie Stout: That was just a follow-up on your compensation question and point.

561
00:46:40.990 --> 00:46:50.989
Julie Stout: So this is a final question for you regarding the Doris and Gary project. It's regarding your… the impact, legacy, and your reflection on it.

562
00:46:51.170 --> 00:46:59.930
Julie Stout: What lasting impacts stand out for participants, IU, and the field, and what lessons or advice would you pass on to future stewards?

563
00:47:04.300 --> 00:47:05.880
John Hasse: Could you repeat the question, please?

564
00:47:05.880 --> 00:47:06.980
Julie Stout: Yeah, of course.

565
00:47:07.450 --> 00:47:23.480
Julie Stout: What lasting impacts stand out about the project? For the participants, for IU, and the field itself? And what lessons or advice would you pass on to people who… for future stewards, for people who want to conduct work like this in the future? And for people who want to care for the collection?

566
00:47:24.560 --> 00:47:25.660
John Hasse: Impacts.

567
00:47:28.400 --> 00:47:32.670
John Hasse: I think you'd have to track down the informants.

568
00:47:33.120 --> 00:47:36.640
John Hasse: And ask them if it made any difference to them at all.

569
00:47:37.310 --> 00:47:40.700
John Hasse: I don't remember whether Any of the…

570
00:47:40.860 --> 00:47:45.830
John Hasse: Results, or you could say end products, of the Gary Project, wherever

571
00:47:46.680 --> 00:47:51.180
John Hasse: Taken back to the region and presented To the public there.

572
00:47:51.570 --> 00:47:55.230
John Hasse: You'd think… You'd think that Dawson would have done that, but I just…

573
00:47:55.480 --> 00:47:57.240
John Hasse: I don't believe that I went back.

574
00:47:57.860 --> 00:48:03.370
John Hasse: So, this may have been a… just a… Momentary blip.

575
00:48:03.960 --> 00:48:07.020
John Hasse: for most… of the informants.

576
00:48:07.740 --> 00:48:10.320
John Hasse: It's very possible they never heard of Dortson, or…

577
00:48:10.790 --> 00:48:17.570
John Hasse: or the Gary Project, or any of the people in it, again, that's one of the regrets.

578
00:48:18.650 --> 00:48:21.909
John Hasse: that I have when I… Go out into the field.

579
00:48:22.170 --> 00:48:25.450
John Hasse: Which I often did in my job at the Smithsonian.

580
00:48:25.850 --> 00:48:28.090
John Hasse: And I get to meet these wonderful people.

581
00:48:28.510 --> 00:48:33.029
John Hasse: And they're generous, they give of their time, They're bright, they're interesting.

582
00:48:33.890 --> 00:48:38.900
John Hasse: And I go back… You know, enriched.

583
00:48:39.700 --> 00:48:45.680
John Hasse: But… there isn't the time, or I didn't make the time, Jeez.

584
00:48:46.270 --> 00:48:49.040
John Hasse: Build a long-term friendship, to stay in touch with them.

585
00:48:49.670 --> 00:48:52.819
John Hasse: And… you know, if I had.

586
00:48:52.950 --> 00:48:55.659
John Hasse: I would have had a lot less time to go out and meet.

587
00:48:56.010 --> 00:48:57.710
John Hasse: more people than I needed to.

588
00:48:58.010 --> 00:48:59.510
John Hasse: You know, collect from.

589
00:48:59.770 --> 00:49:06.089
John Hasse: So… In that sense, it was a blip for me, since I…

590
00:49:06.490 --> 00:49:08.620
John Hasse: I don't think I had any…

591
00:49:09.670 --> 00:49:12.979
John Hasse: communication with any of the people that I worked with again.

592
00:49:14.160 --> 00:49:17.949
John Hasse: I did… Put together a little audio sampler.

593
00:49:18.520 --> 00:49:25.829
John Hasse: And I sent it to Moses Ash, Who is the founder and… Owner of Folkways Records.

594
00:49:26.300 --> 00:49:30.770
John Hasse: In New York City, legendary company that issued Folk and world music.

595
00:49:31.300 --> 00:49:35.860
John Hasse: And I was proposing to him, LP of Gospel and Gary.

596
00:49:36.350 --> 00:49:38.910
John Hasse: And he wrote right back, yes, let's do it!

597
00:49:39.090 --> 00:49:43.210
John Hasse: But I was… I was just swamped with,

598
00:49:44.060 --> 00:49:46.900
John Hasse: my dissertation and everything else, and I didn't pursue it.

599
00:49:47.520 --> 00:49:51.860
John Hasse: If I had, of course, I would have gone back to… The people on the recording.

600
00:49:52.350 --> 00:49:53.690
John Hasse: Track them all down.

601
00:49:54.110 --> 00:49:59.199
John Hasse: asked their permission and gotten it in writing, and if there was any money coming from Folkways.

602
00:49:59.350 --> 00:50:01.000
John Hasse: Would have wanted to share it with them.

603
00:50:01.650 --> 00:50:02.720
John Hasse: But that didn't happen.

604
00:50:02.900 --> 00:50:12.980
John Hasse: So… Impact on me, I think it made me a better cultural worker.

605
00:50:14.250 --> 00:50:21.850
John Hasse: You know, when you're… When you're working across cultures.

606
00:50:22.560 --> 00:50:26.269
John Hasse: When you're bridging cultures, or people are bridging cultures to you.

607
00:50:26.960 --> 00:50:30.990
John Hasse: As some of my, informant's work?

608
00:50:31.430 --> 00:50:38.260
John Hasse: You've got to… Maximize your sensitivity.

609
00:50:39.940 --> 00:50:41.790
John Hasse: You've got to listen very carefully.

610
00:50:44.150 --> 00:50:46.340
John Hasse: You have to… S?

611
00:50:46.590 --> 00:50:51.660
John Hasse: Ask yourself, Are you really… How sincere you are.

612
00:50:52.340 --> 00:50:56.349
